<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-697-770  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 697 770.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Iandamp;CS (Instrumentation andamp; Control Systems)  July 1990 v63 n7 p83(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Retrofit systems integration project slashes downtime by 95 %.andO;(Automaker Inc modifies welding gantry control system on FMCCorp's Ground Systems Div Bradley Fighting Vehicle productionline)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Henson, Mike.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Automaker Inc (Stafford, TX), an Allen-Bradley Co (A-B) controlsystems integrator, implemented a cost-effective anddowntime-minimizing retrofit of an automated gantry welder used inassembling Bradley Fighting Vehicles (BFV) in Plant 10 of FMCCorp's San Jose, CA, Ground Systems Div.andP;  Gantry operators sittingat a console on the moving platform visually controlled thewelding process along 1,100 inches of seams, while monitoring andcompensating for numerous critical process variables in the harshenvironment.andP;  The rigors of the operation often preventedoperators from detecting welding problems, downtime was often, andlong overtime hours reduced productivity.andP;  Automaker incorporatedmany FMC operator, maintenance and management suggestions into anew control system based on an A-B PLC-2/17 programmablecontroller.andP;  Downtime and overtime were reduced 95 percent whileweld tolerances were improved.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   FMC Corp. Ground Systems Div. (automation).andO;Ticker:    FMC.andO;Topic:     Control SystemsWeldingRetrofittingWeapons.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>